I have written the `candidate.py` model as requested. 

In this iteration, I focused on the instruction to "try a higher-variance alternative if progress has stalled". Since the current best model from Iteration 0 (`iter0_candidate1`) relies on a Bayesian Diagnosticity model with three rigidly specified alternatives (`ALT_SWITCH_PROB = 0.95`, `STREAK_SWITCH_PROB = 0.15`, and `BIAS_HEAD_PROB = 0.85`), I constructed a more flexible, higher-variance version of the same conceptual framework.

Instead of hardcoding the parameters of the competing hypotheses, this updated model uses free parameters `theta_alt`, `theta_streak`, and `theta_bias` to *infer* the transition and emission probabilities of the participant's actual mental models of "alternating", "streaky", and "biased" sequences. 

The self-check script compiles successfully and validates that the `pm.Data` instances match the required CSV columns (`n`, `h`, and `alts`) and map correctly to the `observed` boolean sequence choice.
